<subSubSection id="C3114BE55C49FFC9FF08F9E6AE08F81E" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB4186E5C49FFC9FF08F9E6AE29F973" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2026]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FF08F9E6AD54F9C9" bold="true" box="[199,312,1574,1598]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described based on an undetermined number of specimens (
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FB59F9E6A93AF9C9" box="[1174,1366,1574,1598]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">einige Exemplare</emphasis>
) from same locality, 
<collectingCountry id="F31C58FE5C49FFC9FEFEF989AD0AF997" box="[305,358,1609,1632]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">Peru</collectingCountry>
, Oroya. The single remaining specimen in Dresden is labelled 
<typeStatus id="54B0A6CC5C49FFC9FBC3F988A81FF997" box="[1036,1139,1608,1632]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">lectotype</typeStatus>
accordingly to fix and stabilize the current concept of the name.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4186E5C49FFC9FF08F94FAE08F81E" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,2026]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FF08F94FAD20F95F" bold="true" box="[199,332,1679,1704]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Discussion.</emphasis>
Using 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A659F5C49FFC9FE51F94FAE5AF950" author="Collin, J. E." box="[414,566,1679,1703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" refId="ref9118" refString="Collin, J. E. (1933) Empididae. Diptera of Patagonia and South Chile. Volume 4, London, British Museum of Natural History, London. Vol. 4, 334 pp., 74 figs." type="book" year="1933">Collin (1933)</bibRefCitation>
key, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FDBCF951AF68F95F" authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1909" box="[627,772,1680,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatula">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FDBCF951AF68F95F" box="[627,772,1680,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. barbatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
runs to couplet 38 of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FC31F951A969F950" authority="Collin, 1933" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1933" box="[1022,1285,1679,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="idonea">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FC31F951A801F95F" box="[1022,1133,1680,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. idonea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A659F5C49FFC9FBBAF94FA969F950" author="Collin, J. E." box="[1141,1285,1679,1703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" refId="ref9118" refString="Collin, J. E. (1933) Empididae. Diptera of Patagonia and South Chile. Volume 4, London, British Museum of Natural History, London. Vol. 4, 334 pp., 74 figs." type="book" year="1933">Collin, 1933</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with the following characters (using the same of Collin's key): eyes separated on frons, thorax with dark ground-colour, antennae all dark, dorsocentral setae uniserial, antennal stylus longer than large, femora without stout bristles or spines below, occipital bristles more than uniserial above, first tarsomere 1 of male dilated (at least as wide as fore tibia, not slender as described for 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FE13F8DEAE02F8C1" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1933" box="[476,622,1822,1846]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="commoda">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FE13F8DEAE02F8C1" box="[476,622,1822,1846]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. commoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), frons with 1–2 pairs of longer bristles mixed with short hairs, thorax grey with four brown bands. The frons in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FDBDF882AF6FF8AE" authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1909" box="[626,771,1857,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatula">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FDBDF882AF6FF8AE" box="[626,771,1857,1881]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. barbatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has several pairs of setae subequal in length and do not fit the next couplet of Collin (39, “frontal hairs all short”). Both 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FC8DF8A5AFBEF88A" authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1909" box="[834,978,1893,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatula">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FC8DF8A5AFBEF88A" box="[834,978,1893,1917]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. barbatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FBC7F8A5A81AF88A" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1933" box="[1032,1142,1893,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="idonea">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FBC7F8A5A81AF88A" box="[1032,1142,1893,1917]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. idonea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a long radial fork, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FF58F849AD45F857" authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1909" box="[151,297,1928,1952]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatula">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FF58F849AD45F857" box="[151,297,1928,1952]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. barbatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section of vein R 
<subScript id="178F1A2B5C49FFC9FE3BF857AE60F852" attach="left" box="[500,524,1943,1957]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">4+5</subScript>
as long as section of vein R 
<subScript id="178F1A2B5C49FFC9FC9CF857AF37F852" attach="left" box="[851,859,1943,1957]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">5</subScript>
(
<figureCitation id="133004EB5C49FFC9FCA4F848AFACF857" box="[875,960,1928,1952]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–75" captionStartId="12.[151,261,579,602]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,558]" captionTargetId="figure-502@12.[151,1436,193,558]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 70–75. Wings. 70, Hilarempis argentifera Bezzi, holotype ♀; 71, H. barbatula Bezzi, lectotype ♂ (pres. desig.); 72, H. carinata Bezzi, lectotype ♂ (pres. desig.); 73, H. elegans Bezzi, holotype ♂; 74, H. gymnaspis Bezzi, lectotype ♂ (pres. desig.); 75, H. xanthocera Bezzi, ♀ specimen from Peru." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5248054" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5248054/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
). Both have the same shape of postgonite enlarged subapically, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FE7AF86FAE2AF831" authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1909" box="[437,582,1966,1990]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatula">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FE7AF86FAE2AF831" box="[437,582,1966,1990]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. barbatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has no posterodorsal protuberance on the epandrium (
<figureCitation id="133004EB5C49FFC9FB65F86EA891F831" box="[1194,1277,1966,1990]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–22" captionStartId="4.[151,261,914,937]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,209,885]" captionTargetId="figure-462@4.[151,1436,195,893]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–22. Hilarempis barbatula Bezzi, lectotype ♂ (pres. design.). 11, head, lateral view; 12, postcranium, posterolateral view; 13, frons, frontal view; 14, face, frontal view; 15, thorax, dorsal view; 16, left fore leg, posterior view; 17, left mid leg, anterior view; 18, left hind leg, anterior view; 19, terminalia before maceration, lateral view; 20, tergite 8, dorsal view; 21, terminalia, lateral view; 22, terminalia, posterior view. Abbreviations: ce = cercus, ce + b scl = cercus + bacilliform sclerite, ej ap = ejaculatory apodeme; ep = epandrium, hypd = hypandrium, ptg = postgonite; ph = phallus. Scale bars: 11–15, 19 = 0.5 mm; 16–18 = 1.0 mm; 20–22 = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5248044" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5248044/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), as is present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B63ED5C49FFC9FF7BF812AD4EF81D" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1933" box="[180,290,2002,2026]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hilarempis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="idonea">
<emphasis id="B97FC47C5C49FFC9FF7BF812AD4EF81D" box="[180,290,2002,2026]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">H. idonea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A659F5C49FFC9FEFEF811AD9EF81E" author="Collin, J. E." box="[305,498,2001,2025]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" refId="ref9118" refString="Collin, J. E. (1933) Empididae. Diptera of Patagonia and South Chile. Volume 4, London, British Museum of Natural History, London. Vol. 4, 334 pp., 74 figs." type="book" year="1933">Collin 1933: 134</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 25e).
</paragraph>
